  <p>
    <alert>Definition 3</alert>
    The <em>greatest common divisor</em> (gcd) of two numbers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>
    is the <alert>largest</alert> number <m>d</m> such that <m>d|a</m> <alert>and</alert>
    <m>d|b</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    That is, <m>\gcd(a,b)</m> is the largest number dividing both <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.
    If we look at our examples from before, we know that
    the factors of 24 are
    <me>\{1,2,3,4,6,8,12,24\}</me>
    and the factors of 60 are given by
    <me>\{1,2,3,4,5,6,10,12,15,20,30,60\}.</me>
    <aside><title>Math Fun Fact</title>
    <p>
      One of the reasons we use 60 for minutes/hours is that it has so many
      possible divisors, so it can be proportioned in many different ways!
      We can talk about 1/2, 1/3, 1/4, 1/5, 1/6, 1/10, 1/12, 1/15, 1/20, 1/30 or an hour,
      and still always be talking about a natural number of minutes without having to worry
      about fractions!
      In fact, 60 is something called a <ref uri="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Highly_composite_number">highly composite number</ref>.
    </p>
    </aside>
    Comparing the lists of factors, we can easily see that the <m>\gcd(24,60)=12</m>, as the largest
    number which appears in both list of factors. But, we can also determine this quickly
    by looking at the two sets of prime factorizations:
    <me>24=2^3\cdot 3 \qquad \text{ and } 60=2^2\cdot 3 \cdot 5.</me>
    How you might ask? By comparing the two sets of prime factors, and taking the largest
    power common to both. So in this case, both numbers have both <m>2^2</m> and <m>3</m> in common.
    But <m>2\cdot 2 \cdot 3 = 12</m>, which is the GCD!

    <row>So by factoring the two numbers into their prime factors, we can simply list which factors are in common
    to determine the greatest common divisor of the pair.</row>
  </p>

  <p>
    We next turn to a related, but slightly different concept.
  </p>

  <p>
    <alert>Definition 4</alert>
    The <em>least common multiple</em> (lcm) of two numbers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>
    is the <alert>smallest</alert> number <m>M</m> such that <m>a|M</m> <alert>and</alert>
    <m>b|M</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Clearly <m>\text{lcm}(a,b)\leq a\cdot b</m>. But again, by looking at prime factorizations,
    can we quickly determine it's exact value? Yes, we can! This time, instead of looking at those in common,
    we want to take the LARGEST power of each prime appearing in either prime factorization.
  </p>

  <p>
    Once more revisiting our two examples, we have
    <me>24=2^3\cdot 3 \qquad \text{ and } 60=2^2\cdot 3 \cdot 5.</me>
    If we want to find the <m>\text{lcm}</m>, then we can rewrite this by using the fact that <m>x^0=1</m> for every non-zero value of <m>x</m>.
    So the prime factorizations can be written as
    <me>24=2^3\cdot 3^1\cdot 5^0 \qquad \text{ and } 60=2^2\cdot 3^1 \cdot 5^1.</me>
    so that they have all the prime factors in common. For GCD we always took the lowest power occuring for each prime factor.
    We'll do the opposite to compute the least common multiple, and take the largest prime factor present in either number.
    In this case, we would find
    <me> M = 2^3\cdot 3^1 \cdot 5^1 = 120.</me>
    <row>
      Sure enough, <m>60\cdot 2=120</m> and <m>24\cdot 5=120</m>, and in this example it is not hard to see that no smaller number is an integer multiple of both.
    </row>
  </p>

  <p>In class, we'll prove the
    <ref uri="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fundamental_theorem_of_arithmetic">Fundamental Theorem of Arithmetic</ref>,
    which will explain these connections. Until then though, let's do some brief practice with the computations.
  </p>

